### Adjusted HTML and JavaScript Integration:

1. **HTML Markup for Images:**

Each image you wish to lazy load should have a `data-src` attribute with the target image URL and a placeholder image in the `src` attribute. This placeholder could be a small, low-quality image, or even a data URI for a transparent pixel, depending on your design needs.

Here's an example how you should structure your images within the HTML code, particularly within your `<main>` tag where your content goes:

```html
<main role="main" id="MainContent">
  <!-- Example of a lazy-loaded image with placeholder -->
  <img class="lazyload" src="placeholder-image.jpg" data-src="actual-image.jpg" alt="Lazy Loaded Image">
  {{ content_for_layout }}
</main>
```

2. **JavaScript for Lazy Loading:**

You should place your provided JavaScript code right before the closing `</body>` tag of your HTML document. This script specifically targets `img` elements that have the `data-src` attribute, swapping that with the `src` attribute once the image is about to enter the viewport, removing the need for `data-srcset` used in the previous examples.

Here is how you should include it:

```html
<body>
  <!-- Your content, including the <main> with lazy-loaded images goes here. -->

  <!-- Lazy Loading Script -->
  <script>
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
      const lazyImages = [].slice.call(document.querySelectorAll("img[data-src]"));
      const imageObserver = new IntersectionObserver((entries, observer) => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            const image = entry.target;
            image.src = image.dataset.src;
            image.removeAttribute('data-src');
            observer.unobserve(image);
          }
        });
      }, { root: document.body, rootMargin: '0px' });
      lazyImages.forEach(img => {
        imageObserver.observe(img);
      });
    });
  </script>

</body>
```

This setup ensures that any image marked with the "lazyload" class and a `data-src` for the actual image URI will be lazily loaded. The JavaScript script effectively listens for when these images are about to enter the viewport, and then it loads them by setting their `src` attributes to the value of their `data-src` attributes. This modern approach leverages browser capabilities efficiently, reducing the initial load time by loading images only as needed.

