Creating a custom CSS code for an announcement bar on your website typically involves defining the bar's position on the page, its background color, text color, and other stylistic choices to make it stand out and catch the attention of your visitors. Below is a simple example of how you might code this in CSS, assuming you have a basic HTML structure for the announcement bar.

### CSS for an Announcement Bar

```css
/* Announcement Bar Styles */
.announcement-bar {
  background-color: #007bff; /* Blue background */
  color: white; /* White text */
  text-align: center; /* Center the text */
  padding: 10px 0; /* Padding above and below the text */
  font-size: 16px; /* Font size */
  font-weight: bold; /* Make the font bold */
  position: fixed; /* Fixed at the top of the page */
  top: 0; /* Stick to the top */
  left: 0; /* Align to the left */
  width: 100%; /* Take full width */
  z-index: 9999; /* Ensure it sits above other content */
  box-shadow: 0 2px 4px rgba(0, 0, 0, .1); /* Optional: adds a subtle shadow */
}

/* Optional: Close button styles */
.announcement-bar .close-btn {
  position: absolute;
  right: 20px;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  background-color: transparent;
  border: none;
  color: white;
  font-size: 20px;
  cursor: pointer;
}
```

### Example HTML Structure

```html
<div class="announcement-bar">
  Welcome to our store! Enjoy free shipping on orders over $50.
  <button class="close-btn" onclick="this.parentElement.style.display='none';">&times;</button>
</div>
```

This example provides a basic starting point for an announcement bar. It’s styled with a blue background, white bold text, and fixed to the top of the page so that it remains visible even as the user scrolls down. A close button (×) on the right allows users to dismiss the announcement bar. The close button’s functionality is achieved with a simple inline `onclick` JavaScript handler, which sets the bar's display style to `none`, effectively hiding it when clicked.

### Customization Tips

- **Colors**: Change the `background-color` and `color` properties to match your site's design and color scheme.
- **Responsive Behavior**: Consider adding media queries to adjust the font size or padding on smaller screens.
- **Animation**: Introduce CSS animations, like a slide-down effect when the page loads, to make the appearance of the announcement bar more engaging.
- **Content**: Update the text within the `.announcement-bar` to reflect your current announcement. If the announcement changes frequently, consider implementing a method to update the text dynamically.

Remember to incorporate this CSS into your main stylesheet, or within a `<style>` tag in the `<head>` of your HTML document if you're testing or implementing the code directly on a single page.
